%N A365097 Smallest k > 1 such that the total number of 1 digits required to write the numbers 1..k in base n is equal to k.
%C A365097 Corresponds to the third term in A014778 when it is calculated in base n.
%C A365097 Does a(n) always exist?  If not, might it be better to change "is equal to k" to "is >= k"? - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Sep 27 2023
%e A365097 For n=2, the first two natural numbers are {1,10}, which have two 1s.
%e A365097 For n=3, the first k=4 numbers {1,2,10,11} in base 3, have 4 digit 1's, which is equal to k.
%e A365097 For n=4, 25 1s occur in the first 25 natural numbers {1,2,3,10,11,12,13,20,etc.}.
%t A365097 a[n_] := Module[{k = 1, sum = 1}, While[sum == 1 || sum != k, k++; sum += Count[IntegerDigits[k, n], 1]]; k]; Array[a, 6, 2] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 29 2023 *)
